File to create: `e2e/sdk-fetch-via-background.e2e.ts`

Follow the patterns in existing SDK test files like `e2e/sdk-fetch-errors.e2e.ts` and `e2e/sdk-utilities.e2e.ts`.

Test structure:
```typescript
import { expect, test } from './fixtures.js';
import { callToolExpectSuccess, callToolExpectError, setupToolTest } from './helpers.js';

test.describe('fetchViaBackground', () => {
  test('makes cross-origin request with cookies', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, crossOriginServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
    const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
    // Set HttpOnly cookie on cross-origin server's URL
    const context = page.context();
    await context.addCookies([{
      name: 'session',
      value: 'test-session-token',
      url: crossOriginServer.url,
      httpOnly: true,
      sameSite: 'None',
      secure: false,
    }]);
    // Call the tool
    const output = await callToolExpectSuccess(mcpClient, mcpServer, 'e2e-test_sdk_fetch_via_background', {
      url: `${crossOriginServer.url}/api/echo-with-cookies`,
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ test: true }),
    });
    // Verify cookies were attached
    const body = JSON.parse(output.body);
    expect(body.cookies.session).toBe('test-session-token');
    expect(output.ok).toBe(true);
    expect(output.status).toBe(200);
  });
});
```

For the domain validation test, use a URL like `https://evil.example.com/api/test` — this domain does not share a registrable domain with `localhost`, so the background handler should reject it.

For the network error test, use `http://localhost:1/never` (port 1 is almost certainly not listening).

For concurrent tests, make 5 parallel requests to the cross-origin server and verify all 5 responses are received.

Important: The `crossOriginServer` fixture must be available in the test. Check if `fixtures.ts` already exports it or if it needs to be added to the test fixture type.
